{"key":"post-12783307","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12783307</id>\n<content>I use filter patch bags for small batches.&amp;nbsp; The water around it needs to boil for 20 minutes or so before the substrate in the bag begins to come up to temperature.&amp;nbsp; At around 120F, shut off the stove and see where the substrate stabilizes at.&amp;nbsp; You'll probably need to turn the stove back on to regulate temperature after a time, but the idea is that in the center of the bag, your casing or substrate mix remains at 140F to 160F for an hour.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Larger batches, I do outdoors with steam in a 55 gallon drum, unless it's straw which I put directly into the pasteurization water.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>12783331</next>\n<prev>12782868</prev>\n<first>12781837</first>\n<last>12783677</last>\n<when>1277215356</when>\n<utime>06/22/10 05:02 PM</utime>\n</post>"}